PART 1 — Create EC2 Bastion Server

Set your AWS region to us-east-1 (N. Virginia) or replace us-east-1 in the commands below with your desired region.

Launch EC2

Go to:

AWS Console → EC2 → Launch Instance

Configuration:

AMI → Ubuntu 22.04 LTS (x86_64)
Instance Type → t3.small (minimum)
Storage → 20 GB gp3
Key pair → Create or select existing (example: kuberadmin.pem)

Create IAM Role 

Go to:

IAM → Roles → Create Role
Trusted entity → AWS Service
Use case → EC2
Attach policy → AdministratorAccess
Name → EKS-Admin-Role

Create Role

Now attach this role to EC2:

EC2 → Instance → Actions → Security → Modify IAM Role
Select: EKS-Admin-Role

⚠ Because of this role, you DO NOT need aws configure.

Security Group Rules

Allow:

Type	       | Source
All traffic  | Anywhere

Click Save Rules

PART 2 — SSH Into EC2

From your local machine terminal:

ssh -i "kuberadmin.pem" ubuntu@<your-public-ip>

For this you can either use ubuntu web application or cmd

PART 3 — Install Required Tools

Step 1: Update System
sudo apt-get update -y
sudo apt-get install -y unzip curl tar git

Step 2: Install AWS CLI v2
curl "https://awscli.amazonaws.com/awscli-exe-linux-x86_64.zip" -o awscliv2.zip
unzip awscliv2.zip
sudo ./aws/install
aws --version

⚠ No need to run aws configure (because IAM role is attached).

Step 3: Install kubectl

KUBECTL_VERSION=$(curl -L -s https://dl.k8s.io/release/stable.txt)
curl -LO "https://dl.k8s.io/release/${KUBECTL_VERSION}/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl"
chmod +x kubectl
sudo mv kubectl /usr/local/bin/
kubectl version --client

Step 4: Install eksctl

curl -sL "https://github.com/eksctl-io/eksctl/releases/latest/download/eksctl_Linux_amd64.tar.gz" | tar xz -C /tmp
sudo mv /tmp/eksctl /usr/local/bin/
eksctl version

Step 5: Install Helm

curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash
helm version

PART 4 — Create EKS Cluster

Create Cluster (Control Plane Only)

eksctl create cluster \
--name observability6 \
--region us-east-1 \
--zones us-east-1a,us-east-1b \
--without-nodegroup

It Takes 10–15 mins

Associate OIDC Provider - 

eksctl utils associate-iam-oidc-provider \
--region us-east-1 \
--cluster observability6 \
--approve

Create Node Group -

eksctl create nodegroup \
--cluster=observability6 \
--region=us-east-1 \
--name=observability6-ng-private \
--node-type=t3.medium \
--nodes-min=2 \
--nodes-max=3 \
--node-volume-size=20 \
--managed \
--node-private-networking

It Takes 5–10 mins

Update kubeconfig -

aws eks update-kubeconfig --name observability6 --region us-east-1
kubectl get nodes

You should see 2 worker nodes.

PART 5 — Install Monitoring Stack

Step 1: Create Namespace
kubectl create ns monitoring

Step 2: Add Helm Repo
helm repo add prometheus-community https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update

Step 3: Create Custom Values File
vim custom_kube_prometheus_stack.yml

Now copy content from:

https://raw.githubusercontent.com/akshu20791/k8s-monitoring-using-prometheus/main/custom_kube_prometheus_stack.yml

Save file.

Step 4: Install Monitoring Stack
helm upgrade --install monitoring prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack \
-n monitoring \
-f ./custom_kube_prometheus_stack.yml

Step 5: Verify Pods
kubectl get pods -n monitoring

All pods should be Running.

PART 6 — Access Grafana

Port Forward Grafana
kubectl port-forward svc/monitoring-grafana -n monitoring 8080:80 --address 0.0.0.0 &

Open in browser:

http://<your-ec2-public-ip>:8080

Login:

Username: admin
Password: prom-operator

PART 7 — Access Prometheus
kubectl port-forward service/prometheus-operated -n monitoring 9090:9090 --address 0.0.0.0 &

Open:

http://<your-ec2-public-ip>:9090

PART 8 — Access Alertmanager
kubectl port-forward service/alertmanager-operated -n monitoring 9093:9093 --address 0.0.0.0 &

Open:

http://<your-ec2-public-ip>:9093

PART 9 — Import Dashboard 

Your can either use dashboard 3662 (or) 15757 (or) 1860

In Grafana:

Go to Dashboards -> Click Import

Enter ID:
15757 (or) 3662 (or) 1860

Click Load

Select Data Source → prometheus

Click Import

Your dashboard will be created.



### CLEANUP (To Stop AWS Billing) ###

1️Remove Monitoring -

helm uninstall monitoring --namespace monitoring
kubectl delete ns monitoring

Delete EKS Cluster -

eksctl delete cluster --name observability6 --region us-east-1

Terminate EC2 -

Go to:
EC2 → Instances → Terminate
